description:
In duff and moss near edge of gravel trail. See second photo. This is the only mushroom I saw along the 0.2 mi trail.
Under a bush which I believe is Vaccinium ovatum (California Huckleberry). (Leaves included in close-up photo.) Nearest trees were Pseudotsuga menziesii (Douglas-fir) and one spindly cedar-like thing I did not recognize but which may have been Incense Cedar. Although I did not notice pine nearby, second photo shows pine needles in the duff. This Location has Sugar pine, and one Jeffrey pine (which is probably at least 100 meters from where I collected this mushroom).
This is a young specimen, veil still intact.
Cap: glutinous; pinkish-brownish (close-up photo does not get color balance right, cap color shown accurately in the second photo), getting darker with age, appears to have bruised brown over time where handled or where in contact with wax paper bag; diameter 2.5 cm, height 1.0 cm
Gills: not visible, still covered by veil
Stem: height 4.0 cm; diameter 0.9 cm, widens slightly at top and at base; color: top 1.75 cm is white, then yellow

description:
A flock of 11 Black-bellied Plovers  at this date as shown in the third photo.  Have not seen any over the last few years. In breeding season, shows striking black face and belly with bold black-and-white checkering on upperparts. In nonbreeding season, more uniformly drab gray with white belly. 
Black-bellied Plovers are found on beaches and coastal wetlands of all coasts of North America. Feeds on beaches and mudflats by walking or running, stopping, and pecking at the surface.
Wary and quick to give alarm calls, the Black-bellied Plover acts as a sentinel for groups of foraging shorebirds worldwide. Its quickness to sound the alarm allowed it to resist market hunters during the heyday of shorebird hunting, and the species remained common while other species crashed.
The Black-bellied Plover is the only American plover that has a hind toe on its foot—although the toe is so small it’s hard to see, you can make out this toe in the first photo.

description:
Pileus color: Center lighter than margin. Dark “chestnut” brown (6F7) in small areas marginally, through tan shades, to pale orange-yellow (4A3). (Color descriptions per Methuen where noted.)

Stipe color: Apically, pale orange-yellow, like light part of pileus, ranging to darker reddish brown basally.

Annulus: Distinct annular zone in younger specimens.

Spores “reddish-gold” in color under the microscope (spore deposit not taken), wrinkly outer surface, inequilateral, with distinct plage when seen in full side view, and a strong dextrinoid reaction to Melzer’s. Distinct layers noticeable in Melzer-stained spores.

Spore size: Length: 7.3-9.8 microns, average = 8.5 +/- 0.87 microns; Width: (5.3) 5.6-6.6 microns, average = 6.1 +/- 0.44 microns. (Based on only a few spores – will post spore stats based on larger survey soon.)

Hymenium: Cheilocystidia abundant, plurocystidia present but uncommon. Hymenial structures and lamellar trama metachromatic in Congo red.

Comments: I at first thought I saw a very thin apical germ pore in observations of these spores, but images do not seem to bear this out. I have read variable reports about the dextrinoidy in G. marginata and allies – I’d like to know definitively whether that characteristic points toward or away from this identification.

Image notes: Micro images taken on Nikon Eclipse 80i with CoolSnap ES2 microcamera; DIC (differential interference contrast) illumination; objective magnification noted, but total magnification of digital images highly dependent on display size. All images color corrected where necessary and unsharp mask added.

description:
When I was walking around the local park, I saw a flock of birds flying and chirping around. The birds were as small as the palm of my hands. They chirped in a very fast and high pitch sound. 

Their bodies were of a light brown color, along with a white stripping around their wings. They had small black beaks and their tail was short and had a black tip.

When looking around carelessly, you tend to see the tiniest of things when you least expect it. When walking around the park, I came across something crawling into a shrub. When I looked into it, I was a type of spider.

This spider was small and brown. it's body was differ compared to a regular house spider or black widow. It's body had a bumpy texture similar to the stem of the shrub. Supposing it's its' way of camouflaging with the plants and trees.

As I was strolling through this park close to my home, I came across a part of the park were it has a pathway that goes up a steep hill. As i was crossing through, I came across these little insects that were all over the pathway. Each varying in size and form, yet all the same.

These bugs were about the size of a grasshopper. Their bodies were black, yet there back area had red on it. They have wings along with antennas.

description:
Like before, during my walk through the park, I stumbled through a walkway where there these type of shrubs planted across the walkway. These shrubs had to be about a foot in height. 

The shrubs only had these green leaves that were shaped almost like a  star. The leaves themselves had a light green lining on them.

During my walk around the local neighborhood park, I seen similar trees that were planted on the sidewalk that went the whole block down. This particular tree did not have any leaves, probably due to the seasonal changes in the weather.

The tree's bark was of a grey color. The branches were very thin to the point were you could easily snap a piece of. The height of the tree was taller than a human yet not as big to a house. It's trunk in diameter was compared to a lamp post, probably smaller.

Similar to my earlier observation, as i was walking through the park, I came across a distinctive tree. This tree had to be as tall as a 2 story house. It has a medium size trunk in diameter. The leaves were fern like, as the branches were thin and branched out like vines. 

The bark in particular was of a auburn color, sort of like a dark reddish brown.

As I was taking a walk through a neighborhood park, I came across a particular shrub that caught my eye. This shrub was about 1-2 feet tall and has small dark green leaves. This shrub also has small pink and white flowers growing along with a certain type of blue berries.

What is also interesting was that these flowers tend to bloom during a certain period time. As I recall that during the summer, this shrub wouldn't have the pink flowers nor the berries.

Limekiln is a really cool state park. Lots of history, interesting terrain, flora and fauna, a waterfall, trails, and campsites. Why this park was facing closure is beyond me. The location to the entrance did sneak up on me, maybe its the signage. I  was planning on visiting the park out of curiosity roused out of reading the map and a geology text. A short walk through the trails and a lunch on the beach awarded my curiousness and I can't wait to go back. I hope this place continues to be a State campground for the future, and if you are ever driving along the 1 and you need a little break take it here.
